    "content_hash": "sha256:c8933479e4a37883280d8efeb9922f30181f0123b89e085dbfc8e56d0840ebc6",
    "summary": "The reign of Emperor Aurelian (270–275 AD) represented the most remarkable recovery in Roman history — a five-year period in which a single emperor reversed the near-total dissolution of the empire caused by the [[event:2025|Crisis of the Third Century]], defeated and reabsorbed the breakaway [[event:2855|Palmyrene Empire]] in the east and the [[event:2856|Gallic Empire]] in the west, repelled multiple barbarian invasions, and left behind a unified empire that his successors could build upon — earning him the title 'Restorer of the World' (Restitutor Orbis). Aurelian was a brilliant soldier from Illyricum (modern Balkans) who rose through military ranks to seize power during the chaotic 260s–270s.\n\nAurelian's military campaigns were extraordinarily active: he drove the Alemanni back across the Alps and the Danube, defeated the Vandals, recaptured the Dacian provinces (then abandoned them as indefensible, withdrawing to the Danube line), marched east to defeat Queen Zenobia of Palmyra at the battles of Immae and Emesa (272 AD), captured Zenobia and Palmyra, then immediately turned west to defeat the Gallic Empire. He also built the famous Aurelian Walls around Rome (still largely standing) — the first circuit of walls around the city in 600 years, a stark acknowledgment that even Rome was no longer safe. Aurelian was assassinated by his own officers in 275 AD before completing his planned Persian campaign, but his achievement of reunification was permanent — the empire never again fragmented as severely during the classical period.",
